Mar 30 2009 	Popularity of hotel is both blessing and curse	I stayed at the Residence Inn Chicago River North for a spring break trip with my family. Our trip included shopping, theater (Mary Poppins) and restaurant visits, along with a personal business trip to the Merchandise Mart.The hotel is a nice, new facility with standard Residence Inn suites sized a bit smaller for the urban setting. It is in a great location for most Chicago Loop attractions, including State Street and the theater district. We left the car with valet parking and relied on our feet and the CTA (two el stations within three blocks). Valet parking is the only type offered and is EXPENSIVE - $44 per day (i.e., a two-night stay required three days of parking).I am guessing that the great location and the new facility contributed to this being a popular hotel. The Residence Inn shares the building with a Springhill Suites. I don't know how many total rooms are in the 27-story building, but it seemed like a LOT of families stayed at the hotel, even on weekdays. While popularity is a good indicator for the hotel, the sheer number of people does stress the facilities and services:- Free breakfast was packed and often under-supplied;- The wait for valet parking was about 10-15 minutes at check-in;- Elevators take some time for arrival;- The pool is small and usually pretty full of young childrenIf all you need is a nice Residence Inn room and location, this is a great hotel. However, its overall value is diminished by the high cost of parking and the problems of handling a large number of guests.	
